{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_inxs_ver01/data/sn82014519/00414183566/1930090801/0111.xml":{"full_text":"NEW BRITAIN DAILY HERALD, MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 8, 1930.\nVE\nERAN\nLEAVES II. S.\nSQUABBLE\nCOLB\nDiYisions Argue As to \"Who\nWon the War\"\nChateau Thierry. Sept. 8 (IT)\nVeterans of the Second and 26th\nAmerican divisions are disputing the\nright ot the second division to place\nit bronze memorial on the famous\ntower ot Belleau wood.\nThe ruins of that tower, which\nserved the Germans well as a ma\nchine gun stronghold and was only\ncaptured after violent hand-to-hand\nfighting, still stand on the hillside\nedge of the famous forest. But\nabove the door is the bronze tablet\nto tell posterity that there the sec\nond division won undying fame.\nThe I\". S. government is neutral\nIn the affair, but the official posters\naround Belleau wood, now main\ntained as an American memorial\npark, says clearly:\n\"The second V. S. divisions fought\nits way into this forest; the 26th\ndivision fought its way out.\"\nIn spie of that, however, only\nthe memorial of the second division\nis on the old stone tower. Every\nthing else in Belleau wood is just as\n(he armies left it. The German ma\nchine guns are rusting in the shal\nlow pits where (hey stood, and in\na few years all trace will have van\nished of that fortified stronghold\nwhich took so many American lives.\nEMPLOYMENT BAIN\nSEEN WORTS\nGasoline Consumption Over La\nbor Day Helps Boom Business\nNew Tork, Sept. 8 (LP) Signs\nof a seasonal improvement in the\nunemployment situation in the\nUnited States appeared last week\nalong with a moderate increase in\nactivity in most manufacturing and\ncommercial lines, according to re\nports from various industrial cen\nters. In New Tork city, several of the\nlarger department stores have an\nnounced their intention of increas\ning sales staffs before the end of\nthe month in anticipation of the ex\npected fall buying movement. One\nretailer plans to add a thousand\nworkers before the end of Septem\nber. A similar tendency is noted in\nother sections of the country, par\nticularly in the far west.\nManufacturing lines such as the\nsteel industry have rehired a few\nadditional workers following the\nLabor day siut down and production\nof the metal has been stepped up\nfor the third qonsecutive week. Im\nprovement is also shown in the coal\nindustry, where seasonal influences\nare making their appearance. Rail\nroad freight traffic is also showing\nimprovement but continues yell be\nlow levels, ot recent years.\nCoal Business' Better\nAnother source of satisfaction\nhas been the improvement in con\nditions in the coal industry, which\nhave averaged poor over the past\nseveral years. Heavy demand for\ngasoline over the Labor day holiday\nhas further depleted gasoline stocks\nand fuel prices have shown a dis\ntinct firming tendency. Crude oil\nproduction has also been kept with\nin recent levels.\nAn important factor in the im\nproved business sentiment this week\nhas been the action of the stock\nand commodity markets. Outside of\na further decline in wheat prices,\nmost foodstuffs and raw materials\nshowed a firm tone, leading to the\nbelief that the recent downward\nmovement in prices has been ar\nrested. Widespread comment on the\ntheory that business revival await3\nonly a recovery in the stock mar\nket has centered considerable atten\ntion on Wall street activities. Stocks\nhave now recovered all the ground\nlost during the summer and prices\nare around their best levels in\nmonths.\nDROUGHT'S EFFECT\nMAY BE LENGTHY\nProblem Becomes More Acute In\nAugust, Survey Shows\nWashington. Sept. S (UP)\nDrought has dealt a blow to Ameri\ncan agriculture despite the possi\nbility that the surplus wheat crop\nmay be consumed to compensate for\na shortage of corn, according to\ninformation gathered by agriculture\nofficials.\nThe sharpest Impact o the disas\nter may not be felt until mid\nmlnter. Feeding of wheat to live\nstock in place of corn may obliterate\nthe surplus which has created poli\ntical turmoil in the wheat belt.\nSecretary of Agriculture Hyde be\nlieves. However, wheat would be fed to\nstock only so long as it remained as\ncheap or cheaper than corn, and un\nless it could be disposed ot for feed\nat a, price considerably in excess of\ncorn prices the return probably\nwould not satisfy wheat raisers.\nAnalysis of 30.001) to 40,000 re\nplies to questionnaires distributed\nthroughout the United States by the\nagriculture department shows the\ndrought problem to have become\nmore critical during Auguft.\nHyde authorized th\" statmem\nhere that the shortage of feed crops\nnow is developing into a national\nrather than a local issue.\nIn partial compensation for vast\ndamage to feed srains, Hyd held\nout to wheat producers the prospect\nthat their surplus would be dispos\ned of as a substitute for corn in\nfattening stock. This would pre\nvent 8, burdensome carry over of\nth current wheat crop into the next\ncrop season.\nThis prediction w.ts ronditional\nupon human consumption this vfnr\napproximating the average human\nwheat consumption during the past\nfive years, Hyde said. Wheat sold\nalmost 15 cents a bushel lower than\ncorn on the Chicago market at the\nclose Saturday although bushel for\nbushel wheat is about 12 per cent\nmore valuable as feed than corn.\nHAIR NEW CLU\nKIDNAP!\nNG CHARGE\nLocks Found in Bottom of Old\nTrunk At Oneonta\nOneonta, N. Y., Sept. 8 P Three\ncurls of brown hair found at the\nbottom of an old trunk at a farm\nhouse formerly owned by Charles\nEdward Pope were regarded by po\nlice today as clues linking him with\nthe kidnaping of Grace Budd two\nyears ago.\nThe curls, tied with a ribbon, were\nfound in a (runk in a garage behind\nthe farm house by state police wh\nsearched the premises at the request\nof New York authorities. Polic-j\nsaid the hair undoubtedly was thut\nof a child and resembled closely\nthe color of the Budd girl's hair.\nPope, a 66-ycar old caretaker,\nwas arrested last week when his\nestranged wife told police she had\nseen him with a child shortly after\n10-year old Grace Budd was taken\nfrom her home at 405 West 70th\nstreet June 3, 1 2 S by a man who\nsaid he was taking her to a birth\nday party.\nMrs. Delia Budd. the child's moth\ner, and a neighbor identified rope\nafter his arrest as the man who\ncame to the Budd home ostensibly\nlo hire Grace's older brother as a\nfarm hand. The man gave the\nn;ime Frank Howard.\nDespite the identification, police\nfound nothing else to dispute Pope's\ndenial of the kidnaping charge and\nvere about to release him when the\nhair was found.\nWOM\nFOR\nEN CENSURED\nTEXTILE LOSS\nNew Uses ol Cotton Help Boost\nAmount Consumed\nCLEVER TRICK RESULTS\nFATALLY TO YOUNG GIRL\nYouth's Ability With Rifle Fails\nAfter Two Successful Attempts\not to Shoot Girl.\nNorwich, Sept. 8 \"Teasing\" re\nsulted fatally to Marie R. Woods, 16,\nwho died in the Norwich hospital\nSaturday night, seven hours after\nshe became the victim of a prac\ntical joke perpetrated by Stephen\nKubrosky, 20, who is attached to the\nsubmarine base at Groton.\nKubrosky fled after the shooting\nand has not been seen since. He\nwas shooting at a target with the\ngirl's younger brother in the yard\nat the Wood home, whe he play\nfully pointed the gun at the boy's\nsister who was sitting on the porch\nreading.\n\"Look out, Marie, I'll shoot you,\"\nhe said, pulling the trigger. He\nwhirled the gun sideways as he did\nso. A moment later he again suc\ncessfully repeated the trick.. The\nthird time he whirled the gun too\nslowly and the bullet struck the girl\nin the eye and nose.\nParis. Sept. 8 (UP) American\nwomen's refusal to wear flouncy pet\nticoats and underthings is a contrib\nutory cause toward the worldwide\ntextile depression, according to Ed\nward T. Pickard, chief of the tex\ntile division of the Unite States de\npartment of commerce, who is In\nParis on a survey of the European\ntextile business.\n\"There are two basic causes for\nthe excess of production over con\nsumption,\" Pickard told the United\nPress. \"The first is the diminishing\namount of textiles employed in wom\nen's wear and for household use,\nand the second is the production of\ntextiles by countries like India,\nChina and Egypt which were for\nmerly consuming countries.\"\nPickard declared the foundations\nof the textile industry were \"basic\nally sound\" and that the depression\nin the United States and England\nmight be overcome in a few years,\nproviding, however, clever experts\nfind more new uses for textiles and\nrayons, including artificial wool and\nsilk.\nEvery month, Pickard explained,\nexperts c-C the department of com\nmerce are discovering new uses for\ntextile goods which aids in bucking\nup the diminishing market and tend\ning to prevent the capacity toward\noverproduction to increase alarm\ningly. Cotton street markers and\ncotton airplane roof markers are ab\nsorbing a small percentage of the\noversupply.\nThe most discouraging factor in\nthe world textile situation is Great\nBritain's diminished export of tex\ntiles. England annually exports ap\nproximately 00 per cent of the tex\ntiles produced in the region of Man\nchester. In the past five years her\nexports have been cut in half, or 50\nper cent, by the movement toward\ntextile independence o India, China,\nJapan, and Egypt, formerly heavy\npurchasers of British textiles. Thus\nevery country is producing textiles\nin greater quantities than required.\nThe French market is undergoing a\nserious depression.\nThe Texas game commission has\nbegun a campaign to save the\nwhite-wing dove, prize game bird of\nthe Rio Grande valley.\nFlashes of Life\nBy the Assoriated Press.\nNew York Frances White who\nhas been a highly paid musical\ncomedy favorite, is trying to raise\n53.50. She was locked up in a po\nlice station five hours because she\ncould not pay for a taxi ride. In\ncourt sentence was suspended to give\nher time.\nParis Maurice Chevalier, stage\nand talkie star, is to make $20,000\na week. A theater has engaged him\nat that figure for two weeks in No\nvember. New York The healthiest men\nin prison are forgers and bootleg\ngers. The national prison emergency\ncommittee surveyed conditions in the\nNew Jersey state prison for three\nyears. It found that in physical fit\nness forgers led with 8S.8 per cent;\nbootleggers came next with 85.7.\nBaltimore For his health Ro\nbert C. McCurdy has paddled from\nToronto to Baltimore. He made the\ncanoe trip ot 1,225 miles in 67 days\nvia inland waters.\nNew York James B. Harges and\nCharles Crelghton have backed\nsmall auto from New York to Los\nAngeles and back. In 44 days they\ndid 7,810 miles, the greatest speed\nbeing 11 miles an hour.\nNorth Pelham, N. Y. A small\nautomobile Is utterly unsuited for\nMichael J. Fltzpatrick, chief of po.\nlice, who is a big fellow. He told\nthe village trustees so, exhibiting a\nbuttonless coat, a damaged watch\nchain and over evidence of being\ncramped. The trustees gave him a\nvacation and authorized him to\ndesignate a little cop as his chauf\nfeur. Montgomery, N. Y. Having\ntraveled 1,660,000 miles by locomo\ntive, George Halstein, New York\nCentral engineer, has retired on pen\nsion at 70.\nNew York St. James Lutheran\nchurch, 103 years old, has abolished\nname plates on pews. The purpose\nis to make strangers feel more at\nhome.\nNewport, R. I. Polo appeals to\nsociety more than yachting. The\ncoming international races are In\nsufficient attraction to prolong the\nseason. Many summer residences\nwene closed before Saturday's polo\ngame on Long Island and others will\nclose this week.\nSLEUT\nLOO\nRECOVE\nFROM\nS\nBOYS\nQuickly Catches Young Thieves\nWho Emptied Woman's Purse\nDetective Sergeant P. J. O'Mara\nknows his boys in New Britain.\nThis was clearly demonstrated at\nabout 10 o'clock Sunday night when,\nupon being detailed by Lieutenant\nMatthias Rival to investigate a conv\nplaint from 161 MoClintock road\nthat a theft had been committed\nthere earlier in the evening.\nSergeant O'Mara went to the\nabove address and learned that soma,\nperson had taken 6.20 from apurse\nowned by Mrs. Aloysius Symolon.\nwho, with her husband, was visiting\nher husband's father, Stanislaw Sy\nmolon of 161 McCllntock road.\nSergeant O'Mara asked two or\nthree questions, then went out and\nbegan a search in the neighborhood.\nHe was looking for a boy who had\nbeen in the toils of the police be\nfore. He found the boy, with a\ncompanion, both aged 13, and ab\nruptly asked, \"Where Is the money\nyou took?\"\nThe boys, believing that Sergeant\nO'Mara knew even their secret\nthoughts, confessed to taking the\nmoney from the purse while the Sy\nmolon family was in another room,\nand knowing that nobody saw them\nin the room where the purse was,\nwere mystified by the sergeant's\nquick knowledge of their crime.\nThey turned over S4.S5 to the\nofficer, and confessed that they had\nspent the rest in a wild time at the\nmovies, buying candy, etc., all in\ntwo short hours.\nSergeant O'Mara made a report to\nMiss Ruth Bristoll, juvenile proba\ntion officer, and the boys may be\nseverely spoken to today by Miss\nBristoll.\nThe education building at the\nUniversity of Texas soon is to be\nnamed Sutton hall in honor of Wil\nliam S. Sutton, Texas educator.\nTh i\nmm proved!\nPPET\nadvanced in Beauty-Comfort\n-Smoothness Safety\n7 Lrul\nSee the Improved Whippet\ndrive end you will be sur\nprised to lecrn how far a very\nmodest expenditure goes In\nbuying quality transportation.\nHere is a car retaining all the\nfundamental features of de\nsign and construction which\nmade the original Whippet fa\nmous for style, roominess,\npower, stamina end economy.\nBut this Improved Whippet of\nfers new colors and added re\nfinement of detail for greater\nbeauty; four double-acting hy\ndraulic shock eliminators for\ngreater riding comfort; rubber\nInsulated engine for greater\nsmoothness; internal four\nwheel brakes, fully enclosed,\nfor greater safety.\nWORLD'S LOWEST-PRICED\nFOUR-DOOR SEDAN\n:-;3:san3er\"Coupa $525; 4-passeitger Coups $353)\nCommercial Chassis $360. Prices f. a. b. Toledo, Ohio.\nWILLYS-OVERLAND INC., TOLEDO, OHIO\nELMER AUTOMOBILE COMPANY\n22 MAIN STREET TELEPHONE 1513\nDevelopments in Automobile\nField as Described by Agents\nChrysler eights, recently Introduced\ntrere driven more than 200,000\nmiles in such tests before they were\nannounced to the public.\nRecord Breaking Drive\nBy New Buick Eight\nDriving a new Buick .Eight,\n\"Stu\" Hawley, chief of the road map\ndivision of the Texas Company has\nestablished a new transcontinental\nand return record. Hawley broke\nthe previous record from Los\nAngeles to New York and return-fey;\n15 hours and 26 minutes.\nIn making the sensational drive\nHawley used to stock model Buick\nEight coupe taken right off the fac\ntory assembly line, and throughout\nthe trip it was fueled with regular\nTexaco gasoline and motor oil.\nHawley's total elapsed time for the\ntrip was 141 hours and 38 minutes.\nThe purpose of the record break\ning drive was to prove that it is\npossible to travel across the conti\nnent in less than four days without\nundue haste or hardship. Some few\nyears ago nine days was considered\nthe maximum for such a journey.\n\"The new Buick Eight is the\ngreatest performer in its field,\" said\nHawley at the completion of the\ndrive, \"my trip has absolutely con\nvinced ie of that fact. Throughout\nthe entire journey the Buick deliv\nered its full measure of perform\nance and comfort. It was the most\nthrilling drive of my life.\"\nCadillac and La Salle\nNew Models Announced\nAnnouncement of complete new\nlines of Cadillac and LaSalle V\nElghts was made Saturday by Law\nrence P. Fisher, Cadillac president.\nThe new cars are more powerful,\nfaster, more flexible than any eights\nCadillac has ever built.; and, in ad\ndition, -display unique style and ap\npearance features which establish\nnew high standards ot design for\ncars in their price class.\n\"Cadillac now has a program un\nequalled in the entire history of the\nindustry four distinct lines of au\ntomobiles the LaSalle V-8, the\nCadillac V-12 (soon to be announc\ned) and the Cadillac V-16 which in\nstyle, finish and appointment are\nbeyond anything we have ever be\nfore thought possible,\" says head of\nTabor Cadillac Corp., local dealer.\n\"These new cars embody every\nseund. high principle established\nby Cadillac throughout its 30 years,\nand surpass all previous Cadillac\nand LaSalle eights in performance\nand beauty.\nSix Fisher custom body styles and\nfour Fleetwood special custom bod\nies comprise the complete line\nmented on the Cadillac chassis,\nwhile the LaSalle line consists of\nseven Fishor body styles and five\nFleetwood special custom built\nmodels. The bodies of the Cadillac\nmodels reveal an entirely new de\nsign motif, while the LaSalles con\ntinue along the lines which have\nalready made them accepted styles\nleaders.\n.Equally fine is Cadillac's harmon\nized steering with the new hour\nglass design worm and sector steer\ning which gives the maximum ease\nof operation and makes the car\nhandle readily even when driven by\na woman or girl. The steering sys\ntem is not affected by road reac\ntion. A modulator at the front of\nthe left front spring (a flexible\nshackle mounted on four coil\nsprings) effectually prevents shimmy\nand road tramp.\nChevrolet Introduces One\nAnd One-Half Ton Truck\nIntroduction of a new one and\none-halt ton truck by the Chevrolet\nMotor company was announced last\nweek by the Chevrolet Motor Co.\nComing directly after the an\nnouncement by Chevrolet that pro\nduction of light delivery trucks for\nthe first six months of this year ex\nceeded the same period last year by\ntwenty per cent, the introduction of\nthis improved larger truck seems\ndestined to add to the growing im\nportance of Chevrolet in the low\npriced commercial car field. More\nthan 1. 1C0. 000 trucks have been\nbuilt by Chevrolet since the corry\npsny began to turn out this type.\n.The new chassis is built complete\nwith cab, and affiliations with body\nmanufacturers enable the purchaser\nto choose the exact type of body for\nthe work to be done from thirty,\nsix different types. Chevrolet deal\ners are supplied with complete de\ntails on the various bodies available.\nChrysler Cars Are\nGiven Severe Tests\nAll Chryfler cars are designed\nand tested in the engineering labor\natories of Chrysler Motors where\nmore than 500 technical experts are\nconstantly at work to find some\nthing new and better in automotive\nappearance and performance. In\naddition, all new Chrysler cars are\ngiven exhaustive road tests, extend\ning from coast to coast. The new\nPackard Announces a\nNew Series of Eights\nAn invitation to the public to in\nspect the new Packard eights, ex\ntended by Honeyman Auto Sales Co.,\n200 East Main street, local Packard\ndealers, will appear in tomorrow's\nissue of the Herald. Their new cars\ncomprise more notable Improve\nments than any Packards of recent\nyears. While the characteristic\nPackard appearance and the straight\neight motor have been retained,\nmany refinements have been added.\nThe new models go on display in\nall Packard showrooms throughout\nthe country beginning tomorrow,\nwith the popular standard eight\nfive-passenger sedan offered at a\nprice substantially lower than that\nat which the previous model w-as introduced.\nWETHERSFIELD LIFER\nAWARDED WAR MEDAL\nItalian Government Award Present\ned to Prison Chaplain For Pris\noner Vnable to Leave Cell\nHartford, Sept. S John 'GatturrI,\nlife prisoner in Wethersfield, was\nawarded a bronie medal yesterday\nmorning tor his World War record\nof serving four years in the Italian\narmy.\nHe was not present when the\nmedal was presented, being confin\ned to his cell. Chaplain William\nSmith received it on his behalf.\nThe medal, known as the Istiteita\nMedal, awarded by the Italian gov\nernment to those serving In the war\nfor a year or more, was presented\nby Salvatore Lantieri, vice president\nof the Associazione Nazion&le Ex\nCombattant Italiani of Hartford.\nInjuries Prove Fatal\nto Plane Crash Victim\nNewMilford, Sept. E. R.\nBooth, S9 Maiden Lane, New York,\none of two men injured Saturday\nnear Washington, Conn., when their\nplane crashed, died last night of\nburns in the New Milford hospital.\nJohn A. Cooke, pilot of the plane, is\nconfined to the hospital with a\nbroken jaw and numerous cuts.\nThe two were on their way to\nBradford, N. H., when the plane\nburst Into flames. The pilot nosed\nthe ship sharply but in landing,\nstruck a tree. He leaped from the\nplane and pulled Booth out also.\nThere are 43 holders of glider\npilot licenses in the United States.\nWAR ACE CRASHES\nAT LEWS SHOW\nCapt. John Donaldson Meets\nDeath In Knnz Plane\nPhiladelphia, Sept. 8 W) Captain\nO. Donaldson, 32, World War ace,\narmy instructor and commercial\naviation executive, crashed to his\ndeath yesterday while doing acro\nbatic flying at the conclusion of the\nAmerican Legion air race at the\nmunicipal stadium.\nFlying the plane of Mrs. Opal\nKunz, New York aviatrix, Donald\nson, whose home was in Newark, N.\nJ., and several other aviators were\nentertaining the crowd with fancy\nflying and stunts. Suddenly the\ncaptain's plane went into a tail spin\nand plunged to earth. Donaldson\nsuffered a factured skull and inter\nnal injuries, and died shortly after\nbeing extricated from the wreckage\nof the plane.\nSaid to be the fourth ranking\nAmerican World War ace, Captain\nDonaldson was credited with eight\nvictories over German airplanes. He\nhad received a number of decora\ntions for valor, among them the\nDistinguished Service Cross and the\nBritish Distinguished Flying Cross.\nThe latter wa3 presented personally\nby the Prince of Wales.\nCHICAGO OPERA HOUSE\nWILL BE GOLF COURSE\nReceiver Believes Tom Thumb Fad\nWill Help Pay Off Bonds\nMow Falling Due.\nChicago, Sept. S Shades of Pat\nti. Melb and Caruso! The Auditor,\nlum theater, long the aristocratic\nhome of opera and the better things\nof cultural life, is being turned into\na miniature golf course.\nOpera never was a paying propo\nstion. The auditorium now is in\nthe hands of a receiver.' Bonds for\n$S34,000 issued 40 years ago, are\nunderstood to be due and payable.\nMiniature golf course may be the\nanswer, the receiver, R. Floyd\nClinch, believes.\nThe plan is to have a six hoi\ncourse in the foyer, an lS-hole\ncourse in the main floor circled by\nthe once famous \"diamond horse,\nshoe\" of boxes and with the seen\nof a country club overlooking the.\ncourse from the stage.\nJr tcmtmUot Tmtptt film\nA Mew 6-cyIiinidler\nChevrolet Tiryck\nwith Dual Wheels\nNEW\nHEAVIER\nREAR AXLE\nFOUR-SPEED\nTRANSMISSION\n6-CYLINDER\n50-KORSEPOWER ENGINE\nfkrt L 7\nNEW LARGER tM,\nTRUCK CLUTCH X Ml\nN&yy 1 BRAKES\nDUAL\nWHEELS\ntight Delivery Chassli '365\nLight Delivery Chassis\nwilhCob 470\n(Pick-up box extra)\nRoadster Delivery 440\n(Pick-up box extra)\nSedan Delivery '595\nP4-Ton Chassis with Cab '625\nUTILITY 1V4-TON CHASSIS\nI T\nHe of I Vi-ort ehojiis with or without\ncob includes front fender and apront,\nrunning boardi, cowf, doir and com\nplete! equipped instrument pane, hood,\nhead lamps and Jpare rim.\nDUAL WHEELS $25 EXTRA\nen lVfc-ton models including spare wheel.\nAll prices f. o. b. Flint, Michigan\nCHEVROLET\nWISE\nA new six-cylinder lVi-ton Chevrolet truck with dual\nwheels is now available at Chevrolet dealers every\nwhere. It is big and powerful, rugged and dependable.\nIt offers many new features, of outstanding value to the\nmodern truck user. And no other truck of equal capacity\ncosts less to operate and maintain. Your nearest\nChevrolet dealer will gladly give you a trial load\ndemonstration anytime.\nFEATURES OF THE NEW CHEVROLET TRUCK\nDual wheels at slight additional cost, with six truck-type\ncord tires bigger, heavier rear axle completely\nenclosed four-wheel brakes new heavy-duty truck\ntype clutch new, stronger steel channel frame\n4-speed transmission 50-horsepower valve-in-head\nsix-cylinder engine.\nMOTOR. COMPANY, DETROIT, MICHIGAN\nllvltlen f General Motors Ceraoratlen\nT O\nCHOOSE\nA\nS I X","height":"25700","width":"19316"}}
